HTML

*) Data attributes in html

- Any attribute whose name starts with data- is valid HTML. These attributes are ignored by the browser for rendering,
  but they allow you to store custom information on an HTML element.
  Eg : <div
           data-name="John"
           data-age="25"
           data-id="123">
           data-resource-path="${resource.path}"
           data-page-path="${currentPage.path}"
           data-title="${properties.title}">
       </div>
       - You can create any name you want - data-user-id
                                            data-component
                                            data-product-id
                                            data-price
                                            data-author

- They are commonly used to pass information from the server-rendered HTML to JavaScript.
  Eg: <div data-resource-path="${resource.path}"></div>

- Accessing Data Attributes in JavaScript
    - Exactly. A data-* attribute belongs to an HTML element, so you need a reference to that element before you can access its dataset.
    - Approach 1: <div
                      id="card"
                      data-name="John"
                      data-age="25"
                      data-city="Hyderabad">
                  </div>

               - JS : const card = document.getElementById("card");
                      console.log(card.dataset.name);
                      console.log(card.dataset.age);
                      console.log(card.dataset.city);

   - Approach 2: Using "this" inside an event handler, When an event handler is attached, this (or event.currentTarget) refers
                 to the element that the handler is bound to.
                   eg: <button data-id="123">Click Me</button>

                       const button = document.querySelector("button");
                       button.addEventListener("click", function () {
                           console.log(this.dataset.id);
                       });

